docs.abstract: In 1965, it was the third-most-popular baby name in the United States. In 2018, it was the 635th — and today it’s even less popular. How did Karens fall so far?
docs.snippet: In 1965, it was the third-most-popular baby name in the United States. In 2018, it was the 635th — and today it’s even less popular. How did Karens fall so far?
docs.lead_paragraph: Ask a woman named Karen what she used to think of her name and you’ll hear phrases like “generic,” “perfectly serviceable” and “an easy name.”

headline.print_headline: Not All of Them Want to Speak to the Manager

docs.abstract: Tapestry, which owns Coach and Kate Spade, had hired a law firm to look into the claim against Jide Zeitlin, one of only five Black chief executives in the Fortune 500.
docs.snippet: Tapestry, which owns Coach and Kate Spade, had hired a law firm to look into the claim against Jide Zeitlin, one of only five Black chief executives in the Fortune 500.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jide Zeitlin, the chief executive of Tapestry and one of only five Black chief executives in the Fortune 500, resigned on Tuesday and later said the unexpected move, less than a year into his tenure, was related to a past relationship. The company’s board had been made aware of a misconduct allegation involving Mr. Zeitlin and hired a law firm to investigate, according to a person familiar with the situation who spoke on the condition of anonymity.

headline.main: Tapestry C.E.O. Resigns, Acknowledging Past Relationship
headline.print_headline: Tapestry’s C.E.O. Resigns After Misconduct Allegation

docs.abstract: A forceful campaign by federal law enforcement in Portland, Ore., has prompted an escalation in tactics from some protesters, while others wonder whether they are losing their focus.
docs.snippet: A forceful campaign by federal law enforcement in Portland, Ore., has prompted an escalation in tactics from some protesters, while others wonder whether they are losing their focus.
docs.lead_paragraph: PORTLAND, Ore. — Minutes before midnight on Sunday, the first firework of the evening screeched low over the heads of protesters gathered in Portland, Ore., sprinkling them with white flecks of light and ricocheting into the courthouse that has become a symbol of an unwelcome federal incursion into a local outcry over police brutality.

headline.main: Peaceful Protesters With ‘Room for Rage’ Sympathize With Aggressive Tactics
headline.print_headline: Joy, Rage and Suspicion: Complex Alchemy Shapes a Protest Movement

docs.abstract: Terence A. Monahan, New York’s highest-ranking uniformed chief, was one of several officers who were attacked on the Brooklyn Bridge, officials said.
docs.snippet: Terence A. Monahan, New York’s highest-ranking uniformed chief, was one of several officers who were attacked on the Brooklyn Bridge, officials said.
docs.lead_paragraph: New York City’s top uniformed police officer, two lieutenants and a sergeant were injured on Wednesday in two separate incidents on the Brooklyn Bridge, including one that involved an attack with some kind of stick or pole as protesters marched nearby, officials said.

docs.abstract: The so-called Capitol Hill Organized Protest area was taken over by protesters after the death of George Floyd in Minneapolis. It was the site of at least four shootings last month.
docs.snippet: The so-called Capitol Hill Organized Protest area was taken over by protesters after the death of George Floyd in Minneapolis. It was the site of at least four shootings last month.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — For weeks, officials in Seattle have been grappling with what to do about a protest zone set up near downtown that became the scene of several shootings and a war of words between city leaders and President Trump: Support it as an exercise in populist democracy? Or shut it down?

headline.print_headline: Blaming Gun Violence, Seattle Officials Clear City’s Police-Free Zone

docs.abstract: The movement that started with a few dozen moms in Portland now has offshoots in cities across the country.
docs.snippet: The movement that started with a few dozen moms in Portland now has offshoots in cities across the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the flurry of videos and social media posts that have emerged from the protests in Portland, Ore., activist moms are everywhere. They sing lullabies. They link arm–in–arm, forming a human barricade between protesters and federal agents. Some wear respirators, gas masks and helmets. Some hand out sunflowers.

headline.main: ‘The Moms Are Here’: ‘Wall of Moms’ Groups Mobilize Nationwide

docs.abstract: The London police commissioner apologized to the track star Bianca Williams and her partner after they were handcuffed during a traffic stop on Saturday.
docs.snippet: The London police commissioner apologized to the track star Bianca Williams and her partner after they were handcuffed during a traffic stop on Saturday.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — The head of the London Metropolitan Police said on Wednesday that the force’s handcuffing practices would be reviewed, after officers on Saturday pulled a top British sprinter and her partner from their car and handcuffed them in front of their 3-month-old son.

headline.main: London Police to Review Handcuffing Procedures After Detention of Black Athletes
headline.print_headline: London Police Apologize for Handcuffing 2 Black Track Stars
